              <p><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong><font size="3">November 2004</font><br>

    Vol III, No. 11</strong></font></p>
              <p class="style10"><FONT face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size=3>What Makes the Technical Process Work

</FONT></p>
              <table width="100%"  border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td width="26%" class="style2"><strong>EDITOR'S NOTE: </strong><strong><a href="#note"></a></strong></td>
                  <td width="74%"><strong class="style2"><a href="#editorsnote">IT&rsquo;S ALL ABOUT PROCESS </a></strong></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td><span class="style2"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong>E</strong></font></span><span class="style61"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong>DITORIAL:</strong></font></span></td>
                  <td class="style2"> <a href="#editorial"><strong>AT THE HEART OF THE MATTER

</strong></a></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td colspan="2" class="style2"> The technical and the business press are full of news about standards-enabled products, but almost nobody writes about the nuts and bolts of actually creating them. But without a good process, you won&rsquo;t get a good standard. <a href="/bulletins/pdf/nov04/editorial.pdf"><strong>Print this article (PDF) </strong></a></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td><span class="style2"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong>F</strong></font></span><span class="style61"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong>EATURE ARTICLE: </strong></font></span></td>
                  <td class="style2"><p> <a href="#feature"><strong>CREATING AN SSO TECHNICAL PROCESS &ndash; A PRACTICAL PRIMER </strong></a></p>
                    </td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td colspan="2" class="style2">Most people who create a standard setting organization have never done so before, and may not even have participated in one. Here&rsquo;s how to set up the technical process, from soup to nuts. <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><a href="/bulletins/pdf/nov04/feature.pdf"><strong>Print this article (PDF) </strong></a> </font></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td class="style61"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong>TRENDS:</strong></font></td>
                  <td class="style2"><p align="left" class="style2"><a href="#trends"><strong>MAKING THE TECHNICAL PROCESS WORK (AN INSIDER&rsquo;S VIEW) </strong></a></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td colspan="2"><p><span class="style2">What works, and what doesn&rsquo;t work in standard setting? What do members do (and not do) that makes the process succeed or fail? What trends are affecting the process today? The Directors of Standards of three prominent standards organizations answer those questions, and more. <a href="/bulletins/pdf/nov04/trends.pdf"><strong>Print this article (PDF)</strong></a> </span></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td class="style2"><strong>STANDARDS BLOG: </strong></td>
                  <td class="style2"><strong><a href="#blog">THIS ONE&rsquo;S FOR YOU, ALBERT </a></strong></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td colspan="2" class="style2"> It is said that Albert Einstein once reflected that the Universe is a queerer place than you can imagine. He needn&rsquo;t have looked beyond earth to throw up his hands. &nbsp;<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><a href="/bulletins/pdf/nov04/blog.pdf"><strong>Print this article (PDF) </strong></a> </font></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                  <td>&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td><span class="style2"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong>N</strong></font></span><span class="style61"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><strong>EWS SHORTS: </strong></font></span></td>
                  <td class="style2"><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><a href="#news"><strong>THIS MONTH'S TOP STORIES </strong></a> </font></td>
                </tr>
                <tr valign="top">
                  <td colspan="2" class="style2"> Forking of UltraWideBand Standard Feared; Standards to Curb Remote Control Proliferation; XML Successes and Woes; Sender ID May Not be Dead Yet; Microsoft Causes Concern Over Internet Patents; ISO Adopts More Consortium Standards; Smart Cards Ready to Roll; and <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><a href="#news">much more</a><strong>&nbsp;</strong></font> <font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><a href="/bulletins/pdf/nov04/news.pdf"><strong>Print this article (PDF) </strong></a></font></td>
